% Automatisch generiert — Thema: Abortion
% arg/1 Fakten
arg(pro29).  % [pro] The World Health Organization estimated in 2004 that unsafe abortions cause 68,000 maternal deaths worldwide each year.
arg(pro29b).  % [pro] Many of those maternal deaths occur in developing countries where safe and legal abortion services are difficult to access.
arg(pro7).  % [pro] If the State is interested in protecting fetal life after viability, the State may proscribe abortion after viability, except when it is necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother.
arg(pro71).  % [pro] Americans are more accepting of abortions that occur early in pregnancy when the fetus is not as developed and is not viable (able to survive on its own outside of the woman's body).
arg(pro63).  % [pro] Not all abortions are unjustified according to this argument.
arg(pro63b).  % [pro] Abortion would be justified if the same justification could be applied to killing an adult human.
arg(pro58).  % [pro] Abortion reduces crime.
arg(pro36).  % [pro] The National Cancer Institute (NCI), the American Cancer Society (ACS), and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists all refuted the claim that abortion can lead to a higher probability of developing breast cancer.
arg(pro27).  % [pro] The court also ruled that the word "person" in the Constitution did not include a fetus.
arg(con140).  % [con] Susan B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton led the fight for women's right to own property, to vote, and to obtain equal education.
arg(con140b).  % [con] Susan B. Anthony and Elizabeth Cady Stanton spoke out against abortion.
arg(con23).  % [con] I will always support legislation that would end abortion.
arg(con23b).  % [con] I will always support legislation that would lead society in the direction of ending abortion.
arg(con152).  % [con] For this reason, I introduced S. 583, the Life at Conception Act on March 14, 2013.
arg(con109).  % [con] Half of all women having abortions each year have had at least one previous abortion, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
arg(con109b).  % [con] 8.5 % of abortions reported to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention in 2010 were performed by women who had three or more previous abortions.
arg(con8).  % [con] Fetuses feel pain during the abortion procedure.
arg(con24).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report overwhelming guilt.
arg(con24b).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report experiencing nightmares.
arg(con24c).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report excessive drinking.
arg(con24d).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report drug abuse.
arg(con24e).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report increased promiscuity.
arg(con24f).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report an inability to form or maintain relationships.
arg(con24g).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report difficulty bonding with later children.
arg(con24h).  % [con] Women who have had abortions report other ways in which they are suffering.

% att/2 Fakten  (Dung 1995 — binär; Typ/conf aus LLM-Kandidaten als Kommentar)
att(con23, pro29b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Con's commitment to end abortion contradicts pro's implied conclusion that abortion access should be expanded.
att(con23b, pro29b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — Supporting legislation to move toward ending abortion opposes pro's implied call for increased access.
att(con152, pro29b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Introducing an anti‑abortion act conflicts with pro's conclusion that safe/legal abortion reduces maternal deaths.
att(con8, pro29b).  % [rebuttal] conf=85 — Claim that fetuses feel pain opposes the pro stance that abortion should be accessible to save lives.
att(con24, pro29b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Reporting overwhelming guilt after abortion challenges the pro argument for expanding abortion access.
att(con24b, pro29b).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — Nightmares after abortion present a moral/psychological objection to the pro claim of needed access.
att(pro63b, pro7).  % [undermining] conf=70 — The claim that the same justification would permit killing an adult challenges the moral premise that abortion after viability is justified only to save the mother.
att(pro7, pro27).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — A's claim that the state may restrict abortion after viability conflicts with B's statement that the Constitution does not consider a fetus a person.
att(pro71, con8).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — Pro71 can challenge the empirical basis of con8 by noting the scientific uncertainty about fetal pain at early gestational ages.
att(pro71, con24).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can question the evidence that abortions cause overwhelming guilt, showing studies report mixed or low levels of guilt, especially for early procedures.
att(pro71, con24b).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can undermine the claim of frequent nightmares by citing research that finds no significant increase in sleep disturbances after early abortions.
att(pro71, con24c).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can dispute the assertion of excessive drinking by pointing to data showing no causal link between early abortion and later alcohol abuse.
att(pro71, con24d).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can undercut the drug‑abuse claim by highlighting studies that find no elevated risk of substance abuse after early abortions.
att(pro71, con24e).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can challenge the increased promiscuity claim by referencing research that shows sexual behavior does not change significantly after early abortion.
att(pro71, con24f).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can argue that the alleged inability to form relationships lacks robust evidence, especially for early‑term abortions.
att(pro71, con24g).  % [undercutting] conf=75 — Pro71 can contest the difficulty bonding claim by citing studies that find no consistent impact of early abortion on later child bonding.
att(pro71, con24h).  % [undercutting] conf=70 — Pro71 can question the general suffering claim by noting that many surveys report minimal long‑term psychological distress after early abortions.
att(con140b, pro63).  % [rebuttal] conf=70 — B states that historic figures spoke out against abortion, implying abortions are unjustified, contradicting A's claim that not all abortions are unjustified.
att(con23, pro63).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — B’s commitment to legislation that would end abortion presumes all abortions are unjustified, directly opposing A’s conclusion.
att(con23b, pro63).  % [rebuttal] conf=75 — B’s support for policies moving society toward ending abortion likewise assumes abortions are unjustified, conflicting with A.
att(con152, pro63).  % [rebuttal] conf=80 — B introduces a “Life at Conception” bill, which rests on the premise that abortion is unjustified, contradicting A’s claim.
att(con140b, pro63b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — B states that historic figures opposed abortion, directly contradicting A's claim that abortion is justified.
att(con23, pro63b).  % [rebuttal] conf=92 — B’s commitment to end abortion opposes A’s conclusion that abortion is justified.
att(con23b, pro63b).  % [rebuttal] conf=92 — B’s support for legislation moving toward ending abortion directly contradicts A’s justification of abortion.
att(con152, pro63b).  % [rebuttal] conf=90 — B introduces anti‑abortion legislation, which opposes A’s claim that abortion is justified.
